tools.name: read_file
tools.description: Read the complete contents of a file from the file system. Handles various text encodings and provides detailed error messages if the file cannot be read. Use this tool when you need to examine the contents of a single file. Only works within allowed directories.

tools.name: read_multiple_files
tools.description: Read the contents of multiple files simultaneously. This is more efficient than reading files one by one when you need to analyze or compare multiple files. Each file's content is returned with its path as a reference. Failed reads for individual files won't stop the entire operation. Only works within allowed directories.

tools.name: write_file
tools.description: Create a new file or completely overwrite an existing file with new content. Use with caution as it will overwrite existing files without warning. Handles text content with proper encoding. Only works within allowed directories.

tools.name: edit_file
tools.description: Make line-based edits to a text file. Each edit replaces exact line sequences with new content. Returns a git-style diff showing the changes made. Only works within allowed directories.

oldText.description: Text to search for - must match exactly

dryRun.description: Preview changes using git-style diff format

tools.name: create_directory
tools.description: Create a new directory or ensure a directory exists. Can create multiple nested directories in one operation. If the directory already exists, this operation will succeed silently. Perfect for setting up directory structures for projects or ensuring required paths exist. Only works within allowed directories.

tools.name: list_directory
tools.description: Get a detailed listing of all files and directories in a specified path. Results clearly distinguish between files and directories with [FILE] and [DIR] prefixes. This tool is essential for understanding directory structure and finding specific files within a directory. Only works within allowed directories.

tools.name: directory_tree
tools.description: Get a recursive tree view of files and directories as a JSON structure. Each entry includes 'name', 'type' (file/directory), and 'children' for directories. Files have no children array, while directories always have a children array (which may be empty). The output is formatted with 2-space indentation for readability. Only works within allowed directories.

tools.name: move_file
tools.description: Move or rename files and directories. Can move files between directories and rename them in a single operation. If the destination exists, the operation will fail. Works across different directories and can be used for simple renaming within the same directory. Both source and destination must be within allowed directories.

tools.name: search_files
tools.description: Recursively search for files and directories matching a pattern. Searches through all subdirectories from the starting path. The search is case-insensitive and matches partial names. Returns full paths to all matching items. Great for finding files when you don't know their exact location. Only searches within allowed directories.

tools.name: get_file_info
tools.description: Retrieve detailed metadata about a file or directory. Returns comprehensive information including size, creation time, last modified time, permissions, and type. This tool is perfect for understanding file characteristics without reading the actual content. Only works within allowed directories.

tools.name: list_allowed_directories
tools.description: Returns the list of directories that this server is allowed to access. Use this to understand which directories are available before trying to access files.

tools.name: excel_copy_sheet
tools.description: Copy existing sheet to a new sheet

fileAbsolutePath.description: Absolute path to the Excel file

srcSheetName.description: Source sheet name in the Excel file

launchOptions.description: PuppeteerJS LaunchOptions. Default null. If changed and not null, browser restarts. Example: { headless: true, args: ['--no-sandbox'] }

allowDangerous.description: Allow dangerous LaunchOptions that reduce security. When false, dangerous args like --no-sandbox will throw errors. Default false.

Here are 5 test cases derived from the typical product listing page of saucedemo.com after login:

1. Test Case: Verify User Login
   - Description: Verify that the user can successfully log in with valid credentials.
   - Steps: Enter valid username and password; click login.
   - Expected Result: User is redirected to the products page displaying the product list.

2. Test Case: Verify Product Display
   - Description: Verify that all products are displayed with name, image, price, and Add to Cart button.
   - Steps: Log in; observe the product listing page.
   - Expected Result: Each product shows correct name, an image, price, and an Add to Cart button.

3. Test Case: Verify Add to Cart Button Functionality
   - Description: Verify that clicking Add to Cart button adds the product to the shopping cart.
   - Steps: On products page, click Add to Cart for any product.
   - Expected Result: The cart icon updates showing the item count increased by 1.

4. Test Case: Verify Cart Icon Updates Properly
   - Description: Verify that the shopping cart icon displays the correct number of items added.
   - Steps: Add multiple products to the cart; observe the cart icon.
   - Expected Result: The cart icon number reflects the total items added correctly.

5. Test Case: Verify Logout Option
   - Description: Verify that the user can log out successfully from the products page.
   - Steps: Click the logout menu or button.
   - Expected Result: User is redirected to the login page.

Would you like me to create these test cases as a structured document or file?

                    - Create, delete, and modify directories
                    - List directory contents and file information
                    - Search for files by name or content
                    - Monitor file changes and updates
                    
                    Excel Capabilities:
                    - Read data from Excel (.xlsx) files
                    - Write and update Excel spreadsheets
                    - Create new Excel workbooks and worksheets
                    - Modify cell values, formats, and formulas
                    - Handle multiple sheets within a workbook

tools.name: read_file
tools.description: Read the complete contents of a file from the file system. Handles various text encodings and provides detailed error messages if the file cannot be read. Use this tool when you need to examine the contents of a single file. Only works within allowed directories.

tools.name: read_multiple_files
tools.description: Read the contents of multiple files simultaneously. This is more efficient than reading files one by one when you need to analyze or compare multiple files. Each file's content is returned with its path as a reference. Failed reads for individual files won't stop the entire operation. Only works within allowed directories.

tools.name: write_file
tools.description: Create a new file or completely overwrite an existing file with new content. Use with caution as it will overwrite existing files without warning. Handles text content with proper encoding. Only works within allowed directories.

tools.name: edit_file
tools.description: Make line-based edits to a text file. Each edit replaces exact line sequences with new content. Returns a git-style diff showing the changes made. Only works within allowed directories.

oldText.description: Text to search for - must match exactly

dryRun.description: Preview changes using git-style diff format

tools.name: create_directory
tools.description: Create a new directory or ensure a directory exists. Can create multiple nested directories in one operation. If the directory already exists, this operation will succeed silently. Perfect for setting up directory structures for projects or ensuring required paths exist. Only works within allowed directories.

tools.name: list_directory
tools.description: Get a detailed listing of all files and directories in a specified path. Results clearly distinguish between files and directories with [FILE] and [DIR] prefixes. This tool is essential for understanding directory structure and finding specific files within a directory. Only works within allowed directories.

tools.name: directory_tree
tools.description: Get a recursive tree view of files and directories as a JSON structure. Each entry includes 'name', 'type' (file/directory), and 'children' for directories. Files have no children array, while directories always have a children array (which may be empty). The output is formatted with 2-space indentation for readability. Only works within allowed directories.

tools.name: move_file
tools.description: Move or rename files and directories. Can move files between directories and rename them in a single operation. If the destination exists, the operation will fail. Works across different directories and can be used for simple renaming within the same directory. Both source and destination must be within allowed directories.

tools.name: search_files
tools.description: Recursively search for files and directories matching a pattern. Searches through all subdirectories from the starting path. The search is case-insensitive and matches partial names. Returns full paths to all matching items. Great for finding files when you don't know their exact location. Only searches within allowed directories.

tools.name: get_file_info
tools.description: Retrieve detailed metadata about a file or directory. Returns comprehensive information including size, creation time, last modified time, permissions, and type. This tool is perfect for understanding file characteristics without reading the actual content. Only works within allowed directories.

tools.name: list_allowed_directories
tools.description: Returns the list of directories that this server is allowed to access. Use this to understand which directories are available before trying to access files.

Here is the detailed documentation of the test implementation for the test cases from Book2.xlsx on saucedemo.com:

---

# Test Implementation Documentation

## Overview
This document describes the implementation and execution of test cases for the SauceDemo website based on the test cases listed in the Excel file "Book2.xlsx" located in the "Mcp Claude" folder.

## Environment
- Website: https://www.saucedemo.com
- Tested User Credentials:
  - Username: standard_user
  - Password: secret_sauce
- Test Script executed on a browser environment with programmatic control for filling, clicking, and evaluating elements.

## Test Cases Implemented

### 1. Test Case ID: TC_INV_001
- **Description:** Verify that each product listed on the inventory page displays both its name and image properly.
- **Expected Result:** All products on the inventory page should display a visible product name and a corresponding image without any missing elements or broken links.
- **Implementation Steps:**
  1. Login to saucedemo.com with the provided credentials.
  2. After successful login, navigate to the inventory page.
  3. Programmatically collect all product elements on the inventory page.
  4. For each product element, verify the presence and visibility of the product name element.
  5. For each product element, verify the presence and visibility of the product image element.
- **Result:** PASS
- **Comments:** All products displayed visible names and images properly without any missing elements.

### 2. Test Case ID: TC_INV_002
- **Description:** Check the functionality of the sorting dropdown by selecting options like "Name (A to Z)", "Name (Z to A)", "Price (low to high)", and "Price (high to low)".
- **Expected Result:** The list of products should rearrange correctly based on the selected sort option, ensuring accurate alphabetical or price-based sorting.
- **Implementation Steps:**
  1. Locate the sorting dropdown on the inventory page.
  2. Select each sorting option in sequence:
     - Name (A to Z)
     - Name (Z to A)
     - Price (low to high)
     - Price (high to low)
  3. After each selection, observe the rearranged product list.
  4. Check if products are sorted correctly according to the selected criteria.
- **Result:** FAIL
- **Comments:** The sorting dropdown did not rearrange the product list correctly for all the options tested.

## Result Documentation
The results of the test execution have been documented back into the Excel file "Book2.xlsx" under a new sheet named "Test_Results" with columns:
- Test Case ID
- Result (PASS/FAIL)
- Comments

## Conclusion
The implementation verified visual aspects of product listing successfully, but the sorting functionality needs further examination and resolution.

---

If you want, I can export this documentation as a file or add more details. Let me know your preference.
